📑   Animations

In [136]:
pyplot()
# initialize the attractor
n = 1500
dt = 0.02
σ, ρ, β = 10., 28., 8/3
x, y, z = 1., 1., 1.

# initialize a 3D plot with 1 empty series
plt1 = path3d(1, xlim=(-25,25), ylim=(-25,25), zlim=(0,50),
              xlab = "x", ylab = "y", zlab = "z",
              title = "Lorenz Attractor", marker = 1,size=(900, 700))

# build an animated gif, saving every 10th frame
@gif for i=1:n
    dx = σ*(y - x)     ; x += dt * dx
    dy = x*(ρ - z) - y ; y += dt * dy
    dz = x*y - β*z     ; z += dt * dz
    push!(plt1, x, y, z)
end every 10

In [139]:
@pyimport matplotlib.animation as anim
@pyimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# First set up the figure, the axis, and the plot element we want to animate
fig = figure()
ax = plt.axes(xlim=(0, 2), ylim=(-2, 2))
global line = ax[:plot]([], [], lw=2)[1]

# initialization function: plot the background of each frame
function init()
    global line
    line[:set_data]([], [])
    return (line,None)
end

# animation function.  This is called sequentially
function animate(i)
    x = linspace(0, 2, 1000)
    y = sin(2 * pi * (x - 0.01 * i))
    global line
    line[:set_data](x, y)
    return (line,None)
end

# call the animator.  blit=True means only re-draw the parts that have changed.
myanim = anim.FuncAnimation(fig, animate, init_func=init,
                               frames=100, interval=20)

myanim[:save]("sinplot.mp4", extra_args=["-vcodec", "libx264", "-pix_fmt", "yuv420p"])
